  "text": "In contrast to static high-pressure experiments and natural high-pressure environments, e.g. the Earth's mantle, during an impact event the duration of shock compression is significantly lower and, depending on the size of the impactor, only in the order of ms to 100 ms. Thus, shock-induced formation and preservation of ringwoodite requires (1) heating to very high temperatures, i.e., 41427 1C [CITATION_1] to provide the rapid transformation kinetics required and (2) quenching to low temperatures during shock compression and subsequent decompression within the ringwoodite stability field to suppress back reaction to olivine.",
